WEBVTT

00:00:16.392 --> 00:00:17.850
PHILIP GREENSPUN:
All right, folks,

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:19.410
before Tina is
going to talk, I'm

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:22.200
going to share with you
something that I've never said

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:27.520
to anyone before in 55 years.

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:30.420
I figured it out on
my own by thinking.

00:00:34.230 --> 00:00:37.880
So when you put in the
flaps, the airplane's nose

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:38.840
has to go down.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:45.470
So you put in the
flaps, nose goes down.

00:00:45.470 --> 00:00:46.970
Think about the tail plane.

00:00:46.970 --> 00:00:49.670
Remember, a tail
plane is actually

00:00:49.670 --> 00:00:52.310
flying in the
downward direction.

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:57.000
So the angle of attack
of the tail is negative.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.560
And if you put the airplane
a little bit more nose down,

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:02.930
that increases the
angle of attack

00:01:02.930 --> 00:01:06.230
on the horizontal stabilizer.

00:01:06.230 --> 00:01:08.450
And it can become a
stalling angle of attack

00:01:08.450 --> 00:01:11.960
if that horizontal stabilizer
has been rendered inefficient

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:12.560
by frost.

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:13.740
Does that make sense?

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:16.580
So remember, the angle
of attack of the wing

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:22.370
is positive between the
relative wind and the wing.

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:25.310
But the tail plane is
flying down, generating lift

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:28.070
in a downward direction.

00:01:28.070 --> 00:01:32.390
Wings pull up, tail pushes down
in a conventional airplane.

00:01:32.390 --> 00:01:35.690
And when you go a little
bit more nose down,

00:01:35.690 --> 00:01:38.240
then you have a higher
angle of attack on the tail.

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:40.310
If that becomes a
stalling angle of attack,

00:01:40.310 --> 00:01:43.820
it's not generating the
necessary down force anymore.

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:45.843
So the airplane stalls.

00:01:45.843 --> 00:01:46.760
Does that makes sense?

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:50.740
Francis says, yes.

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:52.143
He's awake.

00:01:52.143 --> 00:01:53.560
All right, well,
anyway, thank you

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:56.350
guys for being here
for that unusual moment

00:01:56.350 --> 00:01:57.370
in my personal journey.

00:02:01.717 --> 00:02:04.880
TINA P. SRIVASTAVA:
All right, now, we're

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:08.940
going to jump into radar,
and communications,

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:10.620
flight information.

00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:13.770
And we're going to do a
little thing that you probably

00:02:13.770 --> 00:02:17.700
haven't done for a long time,
especially not here at MIT.

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:20.140
We're going to sing
the alphabet together.

00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:23.720
So it's going to
be a great session.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:28.490
So we'll start with radar and
Air Traffic Control, or ATC

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:30.260
services.

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:33.830
So what's a transponder?

00:02:33.830 --> 00:02:35.330
Why do we have transponders?

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:37.220
What does it have
to do with anything?

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:41.090
So a transponder is something
that helps enhance your radar

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:44.540
return, so that the air
traffic controller can better

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:47.360
understand where
your airplane is.

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:51.200
So who knows just
generally what a radar is?

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:52.460
Let's step back.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:55.160
Do people know what radar is?

00:02:55.160 --> 00:03:02.670
Who's seen the movie or read
the book Hunt for Red October?

00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:05.190
Goodness, only half the
class, that's really a shame.

00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:11.160
In that situation, we're
talking about sonar.

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:13.980
But sonar, since it's
audible, is much easier

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:15.570
sometimes to think about.

00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:18.900
Well, in that movie, we
have some of the characters

00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:20.370
that are in a submarine.

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:22.830
And they're trying to
find another submarine.

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:25.710
So they send out
a sound, a sonar

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:29.540
that goes out and is supposed
to bounce off of whatever

00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:30.840
is out there and come back.

00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:32.757
So if there's a submarine,
it will bounce off.

00:03:32.757 --> 00:03:34.560
So you hear, you know, ping.

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:38.550
And then if it comes back, they
can hear the sound coming back.

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:43.090
Well, radar works the same
way, but it's above the water.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:46.150
And we use radar
to detect aircraft.

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:48.480
So the air traffic
control center

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:52.980
has a radar that basically sends
out signals that bounce off

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:55.960
of airplanes and come back.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:58.680
We also can use radar
for other things,

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:01.920
like terrain avoidance,
so very complex airplanes.

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:05.130
Not usually your little Cessnas,
but some more complex airplanes

00:04:05.130 --> 00:04:08.700
might have a terrain
avoidance radar system.

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:11.240
So as they're flying along,
they send out a signal.

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:13.230
It bounces off a
mountain and comes back,

00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:15.330
and it tells you there's
a mountain over there.

00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:18.180
Well, we want to make sure
that that return, so the signal

00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:21.360
bouncing off, is very clear and
provides as much information as

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:23.130
possible, so that
the air traffic

00:04:23.130 --> 00:04:27.540
controller knows where you
are and what aircraft you are.

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:28.887
So inside-- yes.

00:04:28.887 --> 00:04:30.720
AUDIENCE: I think it's
